data.content:
Use EF Core 7+ **bulk operations** â€” they execute directly as SQL without loading entities:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update
var cutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoff)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Key differences:**
- Translates to a single `UPDATE`/`DELETE` SQL statement â€” no entity tracking, no round-trips
- Bypasses change tracker entirely, so call these outside any tracked unit-of-work or call `_db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` afterward if needed
- No concurrency token checks or interceptors fire â€” if you rely on those, handle manually

**Tip:** For the 2M log delete, if lock duration is a concern, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```

This avoids long-held table locks on busy systems.
